#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:1
msgid ""
"Assert that two numbers (or two ordered sequences of numbers) are equal to "
"each other within some tolerance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:4
msgid ""
"Due to the :doc:`python:tutorial/floatingpoint`, numbers that we would "
"intuitively expect to be equal are not always so::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:7
msgid ""
">>> 0.1 + 0.2 == 0.3\n"
"False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:10
msgid ""
"This problem is commonly encountered when writing tests, e.g. when making "
"sure that floating-point values are what you expect them to be.  One way to "
"deal with this problem is to assert that two floating-point numbers are "
"equal to within some appropriate tolerance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:15
msgid ""
">>> abs((0.1 + 0.2) - 0.3) < 1e-6\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:18
msgid ""
"However, comparisons like this are tedious to write and difficult to "
"understand.  Furthermore, absolute comparisons like the one above are "
"usually discouraged because there's no tolerance that works well for all "
"situations.  ``1e-6`` is good for numbers around ``1``, but too small for "
"very big numbers and too big for very small ones.  It's better to express "
"the tolerance as a fraction of the expected value, but relative comparisons "
"like that are even more difficult to write correctly and concisely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:26
msgid ""
"The ``approx`` class performs floating-point comparisons using a syntax "
"that's as intuitive as possible::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:29
msgid ""
">>> from pytest import approx\n"
">>> 0.1 + 0.2 == approx(0.3)\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:33
msgid "The same syntax also works for ordered sequences of numbers::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:35
msgid ""
">>> (0.1 + 0.2, 0.2 + 0.4) == approx((0.3, 0.6))\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:38
msgid "``numpy`` arrays::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:40
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np\n"
">>> np.array([0.1, 0.2]) + np.array([0.2, 0.4]) == approx(np.array([0.3, "
"0.6]))\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:44
msgid "And for a ``numpy`` array against a scalar::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:46
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np\n"
">>> np.array([0.1, 0.2]) + np.array([0.2, 0.1]) == approx(0.3)\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:50
msgid ""
"Only ordered sequences are supported, because ``approx`` needs to infer the "
"relative position of the sequences without ambiguity. This means ``sets`` "
"and other unordered sequences are not supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:54
msgid "Finally, dictionary *values* can also be compared::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:56
msgid ""
">>> {'a': 0.1 + 0.2, 'b': 0.2 + 0.4} == approx({'a': 0.3, 'b': 0.6})\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:59
msgid ""
"The comparison will be true if both mappings have the same keys and their "
"respective values match the expected tolerances."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:62
msgid "**Tolerances**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:64
msgid ""
"By default, ``approx`` considers numbers within a relative tolerance of "
"``1e-6`` (i.e. one part in a million) of its expected value to be equal. "
"This treatment would lead to surprising results if the expected value was "
"``0.0``, because nothing but ``0.0`` itself is relatively close to ``0.0``. "
"To handle this case less surprisingly, ``approx`` also considers numbers "
"within an absolute tolerance of ``1e-12`` of its expected value to be "
"equal.  Infinity and NaN are special cases.  Infinity is only considered "
"equal to itself, regardless of the relative tolerance.  NaN is not "
"considered equal to anything by default, but you can make it be equal to "
"itself by setting the ``nan_ok`` argument to True.  (This is meant to "
"facilitate comparing arrays that use NaN to mean \"no data\".)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:76
msgid ""
"Both the relative and absolute tolerances can be changed by passing "
"arguments to the ``approx`` constructor::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:79
msgid ""
">>> 1.0001 == approx(1)\n"
"False\n"
">>> 1.0001 == approx(1, rel=1e-3)\n"
"True\n"
">>> 1.0001 == approx(1, abs=1e-3)\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:86
msgid ""
"If you specify ``abs`` but not ``rel``, the comparison will not consider the "
"relative tolerance at all.  In other words, two numbers that are within the "
"default relative tolerance of ``1e-6`` will still be considered unequal if "
"they exceed the specified absolute tolerance.  If you specify both ``abs`` "
"and ``rel``, the numbers will be considered equal if either tolerance is "
"met::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:93
msgid ""
">>> 1 + 1e-8 == approx(1)\n"
"True\n"
">>> 1 + 1e-8 == approx(1, abs=1e-12)\n"
"False\n"
">>> 1 + 1e-8 == approx(1, rel=1e-6, abs=1e-12)\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:100
msgid "**Non-numeric types**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:102
msgid ""
"You can also use ``approx`` to compare non-numeric types, or dicts and "
"sequences containing non-numeric types, in which case it falls back to "
"strict equality. This can be useful for comparing dicts and sequences that "
"can contain optional values::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:107
msgid ""
">>> {\"required\": 1.0000005, \"optional\": None} == approx({\"required\": "
"1, \"optional\": None})\n"
"True\n"
">>> [None, 1.0000005] == approx([None,1])\n"
"True\n"
">>> [\"foo\", 1.0000005] == approx([None,1])\n"
"False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:114
msgid "**datetime and timedelta**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:116
msgid ""
"You can also use ``approx`` to compare :class:`~datetime.datetime` and :"
"class:`~datetime.timedelta` objects by specifying an absolute tolerance as "
"a :class:`~datetime.timedelta`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:120
msgid ""
">>> from datetime import datetime, timedelta\n"
">>> dt1 = datetime(2024, 1, 1, 12, 0, 0)\n"
">>> dt2 = datetime(2024, 1, 1, 12, 0, 0, 500000)\n"
">>> dt1 == approx(dt2, abs=timedelta(seconds=1))\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:126
msgid ""
"Note that ``rel`` is not supported for datetime comparisons, and ``abs`` or "
"``rel`` must be explicitly provided as a ``timedelta`` object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:131
msgid ""
"If you're thinking about using ``approx``, then you might want to know how "
"it compares to other good ways of comparing floating-point numbers.  All of "
"these algorithms are based on relative and absolute tolerances and should "
"agree for the most part, but they do have meaningful differences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:136
msgid ""
"``math.isclose(a, b, rel_tol=1e-9, abs_tol=0.0)``:  True if the relative "
"tolerance is met w.r.t. either ``a`` or ``b`` or if the absolute tolerance "
"is met.  Because the relative tolerance is calculated w.r.t. both ``a`` and "
"``b``, this test is symmetric (i.e.  neither ``a`` nor ``b`` is a "
"\"reference value\").  You have to specify an absolute tolerance if you want "
"to compare to ``0.0`` because there is no tolerance by default.  More "
"information: :py:func:`math.isclose`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:144
msgid ""
"``numpy.isclose(a, b, rtol=1e-5, atol=1e-8)``: True if the difference "
"between ``a`` and ``b`` is less that the sum of the relative tolerance w.r."
"t. ``b`` and the absolute tolerance.  Because the relative tolerance is only "
"calculated w.r.t. ``b``, this test is asymmetric and you can think of ``b`` "
"as the reference value.  Support for comparing sequences is provided by :py:"
"func:`numpy.allclose`.  More information: :std:doc:`numpy:reference/"
"generated/numpy.isclose`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:152
msgid ""
"``unittest.TestCase.assertAlmostEqual(a, b)``: True if ``a`` and ``b`` are "
"within an absolute tolerance of ``1e-7``.  No relative tolerance is "
"considered , so this function is not appropriate for very large or very "
"small numbers.  Also, it's only available in subclasses of ``unittest."
"TestCase`` and it's ugly because it doesn't follow PEP8.  More information: :"
"py:meth:`unittest.TestCase.assertAlmostEqual`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:159
msgid ""
"``a == pytest.approx(b, rel=1e-6, abs=1e-12)``: True if the relative "
"tolerance is met w.r.t. ``b`` or if the absolute tolerance is met. Because "
"the relative tolerance is only calculated w.r.t. ``b``, this test is "
"asymmetric and you can think of ``b`` as the reference value.  In the "
"special case that you explicitly specify an absolute tolerance but not a "
"relative tolerance, only the absolute tolerance is considered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:168
msgid ""
"``approx`` can handle numpy arrays, but we recommend the specialised test "
"helpers in :std:doc:`numpy:reference/routines.testing` if you need support "
"for comparisons, NaNs, or ULP-based tolerances."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:172
msgid ""
"To match strings using regex, you can use `Matches <https://github.com/"
"asottile/re-assert#re_assertmatchespattern-str-args-kwargs>`_ from the "
"`re_assert package <https://github.com/asottile/re-assert>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:180
msgid ""
"Unlike built-in equality, this function considers booleans unequal to "
"numeric zero or one. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:183
msgid ""
">>> 1 == approx(True)\n"
"False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:190
msgid ""
"In order to avoid inconsistent behavior, :py:exc:`TypeError` is raised for "
"``>``, ``>=``, ``<`` and ``<=`` comparisons. The example below illustrates "
"the problem::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:194
msgid ""
"assert approx(0.1) > 0.1 + 1e-10  # calls approx(0.1).__gt__(0.1 + 1e-10)\n"
"assert 0.1 + 1e-10 > approx(0.1)  # calls approx(0.1).__lt__(0.1 + 1e-10)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:197
msgid ""
"In the second example one expects ``approx(0.1).__le__(0.1 + 1e-10)`` to be "
"called. But instead, ``approx(0.1).__lt__(0.1 + 1e-10)`` is used to "
"comparison. This is because the call hierarchy of rich comparisons follows a "
"fixed behavior. More information: :py:meth:`object.__ge__`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:202
msgid ""
"``approx`` raises ``TypeError`` when it encounters a dict value or sequence "
"element of non-numeric type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/python_api.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.python_api.approx:206
msgid ""
"``approx`` falls back to strict equality for non-numeric types instead of "
"raising ``TypeError``."
msgstr ""

