#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:1
msgid ""
"Assert that a code block/function call raises an exception type, or one of "
"its subclasses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:3
msgid ""
"The expected exception type, or a tuple if one of multiple possible "
"exception types are expected. Note that subclasses of the passed exceptions "
"will also match.  This is not a required parameter, you may opt to only use "
"``match`` and/or ``check`` for verifying the raised exception."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:4
msgid ""
"The expected exception type, or a tuple if one of multiple possible "
"exception types are expected. Note that subclasses of the passed exceptions "
"will also match."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:8
msgid ""
"This is not a required parameter, you may opt to only use ``match`` and/or "
"``check`` for verifying the raised exception."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:11
msgid ""
"If specified, a string containing a regular expression, or a regular "
"expression object, that is tested against the string representation of the "
"exception and its :pep:`678` `__notes__` using :func:`re.search`.  To match "
"a literal string that may contain :ref:`special characters <re-syntax>`, the "
"pattern can first be escaped with :func:`re.escape`.  (This is only used "
"when ``pytest.raises`` is used as a context manager, and passed through to "
"the function otherwise. When using ``pytest.raises`` as a function, you can "
"use: ``pytest.raises(Exc, func, match=\"passed on\").match(\"my "
"pattern\")``.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:12
msgid ""
"If specified, a string containing a regular expression, or a regular "
"expression object, that is tested against the string representation of the "
"exception and its :pep:`678` `__notes__` using :func:`re.search`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/_code/code.py:docstring
#: of _pytest._code.code.ExceptionInfo.group_contains:13
#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: _pytest.raises.RaisesGroup:32 _pytest.raises.raises:17
msgid ""
"To match a literal string that may contain :ref:`special characters <re-"
"syntax>`, the pattern can first be escaped with :func:`re.escape`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:20
msgid ""
"(This is only used when ``pytest.raises`` is used as a context manager, and "
"passed through to the function otherwise. When using ``pytest.raises`` as a "
"function, you can use: ``pytest.raises(Exc, func, match=\"passed on\")."
"match(\"my pattern\")``.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:25
msgid ""
".. versionadded:: 8.4  If specified, a callable that will be called with the "
"exception as a parameter after checking the type and the match regex if "
"specified. If it returns ``True`` it will be considered a match, if not it "
"will be considered a failed match."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.RaisesExc:21 _pytest.raises.raises:29
msgid ""
"If specified, a callable that will be called with the exception as a "
"parameter after checking the type and the match regex if specified. If it "
"returns ``True`` it will be considered a match, if not it will be considered "
"a failed match."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:35
msgid ""
"Use ``pytest.raises`` as a context manager, which will capture the exception "
"of the given type, or any of its subclasses::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:38
msgid ""
">>> import pytest\n"
">>> with pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError):\n"
"...    1/0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:42
msgid ""
"If the code block does not raise the expected exception (:class:"
"`ZeroDivisionError` in the example above), or no exception at all, the check "
"will fail instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:45
msgid ""
"You can also use the keyword argument ``match`` to assert that the exception "
"matches a text or regex::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:48
msgid ""
">>> with pytest.raises(ValueError, match='must be 0 or None'):\n"
"...     raise ValueError(\"value must be 0 or None\")\n"
"\n"
">>> with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=r'must be \\d+$'):\n"
"...     raise ValueError(\"value must be 42\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:54
msgid ""
"The ``match`` argument searches the formatted exception string, which "
"includes any `PEP-678 <https://peps.python.org/pep-0678/>`__ ``__notes__``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:62
msgid ""
"The ``check`` argument, if provided, must return True when passed the raised "
"exception for the match to be successful, otherwise an :exc:`AssertionError` "
"is raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:69
msgid ""
"The context manager produces an :class:`ExceptionInfo` object which can be "
"used to inspect the details of the captured exception::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:72
msgid ""
">>> with pytest.raises(ValueError) as exc_info:\n"
"...     raise ValueError(\"value must be 42\")\n"
">>> assert exc_info.type is ValueError\n"
">>> assert exc_info.value.args[0] == \"value must be 42\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:79
msgid ""
"Given that ``pytest.raises`` matches subclasses, be wary of using it to "
"match :class:`Exception` like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:81
msgid ""
"# Careful, this will catch ANY exception raised.\n"
"with pytest.raises(Exception):\n"
"    some_function()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:85
msgid ""
"Because :class:`Exception` is the base class of almost all exceptions, it is "
"easy for this to hide real bugs, where the user wrote this expecting a "
"specific exception, but some other exception is being raised due to a bug "
"introduced during a refactoring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:89
msgid ""
"Avoid using ``pytest.raises`` to catch :class:`Exception` unless certain "
"that you really want to catch **any** exception raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:94
msgid ""
"When using ``pytest.raises`` as a context manager, it's worthwhile to note "
"that normal context manager rules apply and that the exception raised *must* "
"be the final line in the scope of the context manager. Lines of code after "
"that, within the scope of the context manager will not be executed. For "
"example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:100
msgid ""
">>> value = 15\n"
">>> with pytest.raises(ValueError) as exc_info:\n"
"...     if value > 10:\n"
"...         raise ValueError(\"value must be <= 10\")\n"
"...     assert exc_info.type is ValueError  # This will not execute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:106
msgid ""
"Instead, the following approach must be taken (note the difference in "
"scope)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/_pytest/raises.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.raises.raises:109
msgid ""
">>> with pytest.raises(ValueError) as exc_info:\n"
"...     if value > 10:\n"
"...         raise ValueError(\"value must be <= 10\")\n"
"...\n"
">>> assert exc_info.type is ValueError"
msgstr ""

