#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:258
msgid "pytest.mark.xfail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:260
msgid "**Tutorial**: :ref:`xfail`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:262
msgid "Marks a test function as *expected to fail*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:266
msgid ""
"Condition for marking the test function as xfail (``True/False`` or a :ref:"
"`condition string <string conditions>`). If a ``bool``, you also have to "
"specify ``reason`` (see :ref:`condition string <string conditions>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:270
msgid "Reason why the test function is marked as xfail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:272
msgid ""
"Exception class (or tuple of classes) expected to be raised by the test "
"function; other exceptions will fail the test. Note that subclasses of the "
"classes passed will also result in a match (similar to how the ``except`` "
"statement works)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:277
msgid ""
"Whether the test function should actually be executed. If ``False``, the "
"function will always xfail and will not be executed (useful if a function is "
"segfaulting)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:280
msgid ""
"* If ``False`` the function will be shown in the terminal output as "
"``xfailed`` if it fails   and as ``xpass`` if it passes. In both cases this "
"will not cause the test suite to fail as a whole. This   is particularly "
"useful to mark *flaky* tests (tests that fail at random) to be tackled "
"later. * If ``True``, the function will be shown in the terminal output as "
"``xfailed`` if it fails, but if it   unexpectedly passes then it will "
"**fail** the test suite. This is particularly useful to mark functions   "
"that are always failing and there should be a clear indication if they "
"unexpectedly start to pass (for example   a new release of a library fixes a "
"known bug).  Defaults to :confval:`strict_xfail`, which is ``False`` by "
"default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:281
msgid ""
"If ``False`` the function will be shown in the terminal output as "
"``xfailed`` if it fails and as ``xpass`` if it passes. In both cases this "
"will not cause the test suite to fail as a whole. This is particularly "
"useful to mark *flaky* tests (tests that fail at random) to be tackled later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:284
msgid ""
"If ``True``, the function will be shown in the terminal output as "
"``xfailed`` if it fails, but if it unexpectedly passes then it will **fail** "
"the test suite. This is particularly useful to mark functions that are "
"always failing and there should be a clear indication if they unexpectedly "
"start to pass (for example a new release of a library fixes a known bug)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:289
msgid "Defaults to :confval:`strict_xfail`, which is ``False`` by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:293
msgid "Custom marks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:295
msgid ""
"Marks are created dynamically using the factory object ``pytest.mark`` and "
"applied as a decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:299
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.timeout(10, \"slow\", method=\"thread\")\n"
"def test_function(): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:304
msgid ""
"Will create and attach a :class:`Mark <pytest.Mark>` object to the "
"collected :class:`Item <pytest.Item>`, which can then be accessed by "
"fixtures or hooks with :meth:`Node.iter_markers <_pytest.nodes.Node."
"iter_markers>`. The ``mark`` object will have the following attributes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:308
msgid ""
"mark.args == (10, \"slow\")\n"
"mark.kwargs == {\"method\": \"thread\"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:313
msgid "Example for using multiple custom markers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:315
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.timeout(10, \"slow\", method=\"thread\")\n"
"@pytest.mark.slow\n"
"def test_function(): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:321
msgid ""
"When :meth:`Node.iter_markers <_pytest.nodes.Node.iter_markers>` or :meth:"
"`Node.iter_markers_with_node <_pytest.nodes.Node.iter_markers_with_node>` is "
"used with multiple markers, the marker closest to the function will be "
"iterated over first. The above example will result in ``@pytest.mark.slow`` "
"followed by ``@pytest.mark.timeout(...)``."
msgstr ""

